 interventions","Comparison of outcomes between two treatment groups"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Edetailed description of a single patient or event\u003C/strong\u003E is the defining characteristic of a case report. Case reports provide in-depth documentation of the clinical presentation, diagnostic process, treatment, and outcomes for individual patients, particularly when encountering rare or unusual phenomena.\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options represent other study designs:\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cul\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComparison of outcomes between two treatment groups\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes a comparative study, such as a cohort study or clinical trial\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnalysis of risk factors across multiple patients\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes a case-control or cohort study design\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESystematic review of published literature\u003C/strong\u003E - This involves synthesising evidence from multiple published studies\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERandomised allocation of participants to interventions\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes a randomised controlled trial\u003C/li\u003E    \u003C/ul\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EWhile case reports are considered low-level evidence due to their observational nature and sample size of one, they play an important role in medical literature by identifying new diseases, unusual presentations, and unexpected treatment effects that warrant further investigation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Case reports provide detailed descriptions of unique or rare clinical presentations, treatments, or outcomes for a single patient.","Case reports rank low in the hierarchy of evidence due to their observational nature and sample size of one.","The main value of case reports 